column168: DRIVER WAS EFFECTING PUMP-OFF DELIVERY OF #2 OIL INTO CUSTOMER ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK.  DRIVER HAD OFF LOADED 3 OF 4 TRAILER COMPARTMENTS; AND WAS PROCEEDING WITH 4TH AND FINAL COMPARTMENT WHEN SPILLAGE OCCURED...DELIVERY SITE WAS CONSTRUCTED IN SUCH A WA Y THAT DRIVER HAD TO PULL UNIT FORWARD INTO UNLOADING AREA-CONNECT HOSES FROM OUR TRANSPORT TANK TO OUR TRACTOR PUMP CONNECTIONS AND THEN CONNECT HOSE FROM OUR TRACTOR PUMP TO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK VALVE BY PLACING HOSE UNDERNEATH OUR TRACTOR OVER TO CUSTOMER TANK.  DRIVER STATES THAT AS HE STARTED PUMPING THE 4TH AND LAST COMPARTMENT OF PRODUCT FROM OUR TRAILER TO CUSTOMER TANK; THAT HE WALKED AROUND THE FRON OF OUR TRANSPORT UNIT IN ORDER TO PHYSICALLY LOOK AT THE HOSE/FITTING CONNECTIONS TO CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK TO MAKE SURE OFFLOADING PROCESS WAS PROCEEDING WITHOUT ERROR AND THAT AS HE WASW COMING BACK AROUND THE FRONT OF OUR TRACTOR TOWARD TRAILER.UNLOADING VALVES THAT HE NOTICED PRODUCT WAS COMING DIRECTLY OUT OF THE PIPE/FITTING OF OUR TRACTOR PUMP (THAT OUR PRODUCT HOSE HAD CAME LOOSE AT THE CON NECTION TO TRACTOR PUMP).  DRIVER STATES HE SLIPPED AS HE STARTED, RIGHT HIMSELF AND PROCEEDE TO ENTER I NTO OUR TRACTOR TO DISENGAGE THE PTO PRODUCT PUMP-VACATED TRACTOR AND PROCEEDED TO TRAILER AND TURNED OF F UNLOADING VALVES OF TRAILER.  DRIVER STATES THAT AS HE CAME ABREAST OF TRAILER DURING HIS ACTIVITY OF SCRAMBLING TO SHUT OFF ALL DEVICES (PUMP/VALVES) THAT HE NOTICED THAT THE DOOR TO OUR TRAILER COMPARTMENT THAT HOUSE THE SAFETY VALVE CONTROLS WAS SHUT... HE FEELS THAT THE DOOR WAS BLOWN SHUT BY HIGH WINDSS THAT WERE OCCURING AT THE TIME OF OFFLOADING AS IT WAS RAINING AND STORMING WITH HIGH WINDS THAT THE SHOCK OF THE TRAILER SAFETY SHUTING DOWN THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM OUR TRAILERFROM THE CONNECTION TO TRACTOR THEREBY RESULTING IN A LOSS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND IMMEDIATE TO THE UNLOADING AREA.  DRIVER REPORTED TO OUR OPERATIONS STAFF AN INITIAL GALLON FIGURE OF APPROX. 50 GALLONS OF LOST PRODUCT... SUBSEQUENT INVESTIGATION REVEALED A LARGER QUANTITY OF PRODUCT (1151 GALLONS) WAS LOST.  AT THAT TIME THE OHIO EPA WA CONTACTED ALONG WITH THE WELLINGTON, OHIO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN-UP ACTIVITY WAS UNDERTAKEN AND k & D OF MANSFIELD OHIO WAS CALLED IN TO EFFECT SITE REMEDIATION.  ESCAVATION OF CONTAMINATED SOIL ALONG A DITCHLINE AND SMALL CREEK BOG AREA WAS COMMISSIONED AND CONTROLLED THROUGH ADVISEMENT OF OHIO EPA PERSONNEL. INAPPROPRIATE ACTIVITY OF OUR DRIVER LEAVING THE IMMEDIATE UNLOADING AREA OF OUR TRAILER VALVES AND TRACTOR PUMP AREA IS NOTED AND WILL BE EMPHASIZED IN THE UTMOST AT OUR UPCOMING SAFETY MEETINGS AND TRAINING SESSIONS.  OUR SAFETY DEAPRTMENT IN CONJUCTION WITH OUR OPERATIONS DEPARTMENT IS IMPLEMENTING PROCEDURES WHEREIN ANY LOAD DELIVERY THAT REQUIRES DRIVER TO HAVE A "BLIND" HOOK-UP (THE CONNECTON TO CUSTOMER TANK IS NOT IN SIGHT OF DRIVER WHILE HE MAINTAINS PRESENT AT OUR OFFLOADING TRAILER VALVES AND PUMPS) MUST BE MADE WHILE CU STOMER SITE IS

THE TRAILER WAS THEN REWORKED AND SENT TO ITS FINAL DESTINATON IN CAMARILLO,CA.

column168: WHILE A DOCK HAND WAS UNLOADING THE BOX HE SET IT DOWN TOO HARD WHICH CAUSED ONE OF THE FOUR 1-GALLON GLASS CONTAINERS TO BREAK.

DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE PLANT AND WAS TOLD THAT THE LOAD WAS GOING TO BE DRUMMED OFF.  DRIVER SPOTTED THE TRAILE AND WAS THEN RELIEVED OF ALL UNLOADING RESPONSIBILITY.  HE CUSTOMER DRUMS THE PRODUCT INTO 55 GALLON DRUM WHICH IS SITTING ON SCALES.  WHEN THE WEIGHT GETS TO 700 LBS THE DRUMMING NOZZLE SHUTS OFF AUTOMATICALLY.  DURING ONE OF THESE SHUT OFFS OUR  UNLOADING HOSE BURST CAUSING ABOUT 8 TO 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL INTO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  THE CUSTOMER HAD ABOUT 15 TO 20 LBS OF AIR PRESSURE IN THE TRAILER.  THE HOLE IN THE HOSE WAS ABOUT ONE HALF INCH IN LENGTH.  THE HOSE IS RATED 150 LBS PSI AND WAS MANUFACTURER TO SEE IF IT IS DEFECTIVE IN ANY WAY.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY THE PLANT PERSONNEL.

TRAILER T747 ARRIVED FROM THE CHARLESTON TERMINAL TO CLEVELAND.  IT WAS NOTIFED THAT ONE DRUM WAS DENTED AND LEAKING AT THE TOP RIB.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAIN ON ITS SIDE AND BLOCKED.  DRUM WAS PATCHED PER SHIPPERS INSTRUCTION AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER. MORE CAREFUL LOADING AND PROPER DUNNAGE WOULD POSSIBLY HAVE PREVENTED THIS INCIDENT FROM HAPPENING.

DRIVER HAD 5 FIFTEEN-GALLON POLYETHYLENE DRUMS ON A PALLET.  THE PALLET WAS SECURED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER BY THE PALLET JACK AND LOAD BAR, BUT WAS NOT BLOCKED TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE PALLET.  THE DRIVER REACHED THE CUSTOMER TOOL LATE TO DELIVER THE LOAD, AND AT THE END OF THE RETURN TRIP, DRIVER SURMISES THAT JOSTLING OF THE LOAD WHIL TRANSPORTING OVER RAILROAD TRACKS, CAUSED ONE DRUM TO FALL OFF THE PALLET ON THE UNBLOCKED SIDE.  THE DRUM CRACKED AT THE TOP AND SPILLED IN THE TRUCK, AND THEN ON THE PLANT PARKING PAD AFTER THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRUCK DOOR.  THE SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND ABSORBED. RECOMMENDATIONS TO IMPROVE HANDLING: 1) INSTRUCT DRIVER AND LOADERS TO LOAD LESS-THAN-FAULL-PALLETS LOADS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER OR BAND DRUMS TO THE PALLET, AS WELL AS TO EACH OTHER.  2) INSTRUCT/REVIEW WITH DRIVERS PROPER LOADING AND BLOCKING TECHNIQUES AND PRECAUTIONARY DRIVING PROCEDURES FOR PARTIAL LOADS, TO MINIMIZE POTENTIAL MOVEMENT DURING TRANSPORT.

THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR REPORTED THAT ONE 55 GALLON DRUM HAD TURNED OVER INSIDE OF THE TRAILER, AND APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE DRUM. OUR INTERNAL INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT IMPROPER BRACING WAS THE CAUSE OF THE OVERTURNED DRUM. A MEMO WAS DISTRIBUTED TO THE REST OF THE EMPLOYEES EMPHASIZING CONCERN FOR SAFETY AND THE DANGERS OF CARELESS HANDLING OF CHEMICALS.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HANDLING TRAINING WAS SCHEDULED FOR THE REST OF THE EMPLOYEES (THIS DONE ANNUALLY).  IMPROVEMENTS TO PACKAGING WERE RELAYED TO ORIGINATING SHIPPER. column168: A CARGO TANK CONTAINING SPECIFICATION USED FUEL OIL WAS EXITING THE PROPERTY OF MURPHY'S WASTE OIL SERVICES, INC., LOCATED AT 252 SALEM STREET IN WOBURN, MA EN-ROUTE TO TILCON OF MAINE, INC.  UPON EXITING THE FACILITY, THE VEHICLE PROCEEDED UP A STEEP INCLUDE AND THE PRESSURE OF THE OIL AS IT FLOWED BACKWARD INSIDE THE TANKER GENERATED ENOUGH HEAD PRESSURE TO OPEN THE HATCH COVER.  THIS RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM THE TANK.  THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VEHICLE AND BEGAN TO SPREAD ABSORBENT MATERIAL ON THE OIL.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO CONTACT HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR WHO, IN TURN, CONTACTED THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AND REPORTED THE LEASE. ALL OF THE OIL WHICH SPILLED FROM THE TRUCK WAS CONTAINED ON THE ASPHALT DRIVEWAY AND CLEANED UP WITH SPEEDI DRY AND ABSORBENT PADS BY TRAINED PERSONNEL.  THE CARGO TANK WAS ALSO DECONTAMINATED AND THE ABSORBENT PADS AND RAGS USED IN THIS OPERATION WERE ALSO CONTAINERIZED.  4 X 55 GALLON DRUMS OF SPILL MATERIAL WAS CONTAINERIZED AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, THE TENSION SETTING ON THE DOME HATCH OF THE VEHICLE INVOLVED AS WELL AS ALL VEHICLES BASED AT THIS LOCATION WERE READJUSTED.  ADDITIONALLY, MANUALLY OPERATED SAFETY LOCKS FOR THE HATCH COVERS HAVE BEEN PURCHASED.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL OF OUR TRAILER #555 FROM HAGERSTOWN, MD. TERMINAL AT OUR EAST BRUNSWICK NJ TERMINAL EVERYTHING APPEARED NORMAL. DOORS WERE OPENED AND TRAILER WAS SPOTTED INTO THE DOCK FOR UNLOADING AND CYLINDER WAS LOADED ON THE REAR ON A WOODEN SKID. AT APPROX. 7:30 AM DOCKWORKER STARTED TO UNOAD THE CYLINDER. WHEN HE PUT THE FORKLIFT BLADES UNDER THE SKID AND STARTED TO PICKUP SAME, HE SAW A RELEASE OF VIPER OUT OF THE PRESSURE RELEASE PLUG AT THE END OF THE TANK. THE EAST BRUNSWICK FIRE DEPT. WAS NOTIFIED AND UPON ARRIVAL, THEY EVACUATED PERSONNEL FROM OUR TERMINAL AND FORCED WORKERS WHO WERE IN THE AREA TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED OUT. NONE OF THE WORKERS COMPLAINED OF ANY ILLNESS OR REQUESTED MEDICAL TREATMENT BUT WERE FORCED TO GO TO THE HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM TO BE CHECKED OUT. ALL WERE CHECKED AND RELEASED THAT DAY. MATHESON GAS PRODUCTS RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND THEY WERE DISPATCHED TO OUR TERMINAL TO HANDLE THE RELEASE. MATHESON PEOPLE CHANNELED THE LEAKING GAS INTO A DRUM NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION OF SODA ASH AND OUR TERMINAL WAS ALLOWED TO REOPEN. MATHESON LOADED THE TANK ONTO THEIR VEHICLE, DECONTAMINATED THE AREA AND TOOK ALL RESIDUAL BACK WITH THEM. THE CYLINDER HAD CONTAINED HYDROGEN CHLORIDE BUT WAS EMPTY AND WAS BEING RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER, BUT APPARENTLY STILL CONTAINED RESIDUE.

column168: THERE WEERE TWO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS WITH THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK THAT WERE UNKNOWN TO THE DRIVER. THESE MECHANICAL PROBLEMS THAT WERE DIRECTLY RESPONSIBLE  FOR THE SPILL WERE: A) IMPROPER ALIGNMENT OF DROP TUBE WHICH CAUSED BACK PRESSURE. B) IMPROPER DRAIN PLUG IN FILL CONTAINMENT BOX. DUE TO THE BACK PRESSURE CREATED BY THE DROP TUBE, PRODUCT BACKED UP TO AND OUT OF THE DRAIN PLUG.

OUR EMPLOYEE TOOK OFF HIS GOGGLES AND GOT SOME DUST IN HIS EYES. WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL TREATED AND RELEASED. STAYED UNDER CARE FOR 7 DAYS BEFORE RETURNING TO WORK. FERGUSON - HARBOUR WAS CALLED TO HANDLE THE SPILL AND CLEANED UP.

A LOAD OF WASTE CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS BEING TRANSPORTED FROM AMERICAN PLATING, INC. TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. APPROXIMATELY 2 BLOCKS FROM THE GENERATOR'S FACILITY THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE STOPPED AT A STOP SIGN AND NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE VEHICLE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SPREAD SPEEDY DRY ON THE AFFECTED AREA AND IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AS THE TOP HATCH COVER OF THE CARGO TANK. AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER CONTACTED HIS HOME TERMINAL WHO, IN TURN, CONTACTED THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIROMENTAL RESOURCES. LOCAL POLICE AND FIRE WERE ON SITE AT THE TIME THE INITIAL CONTACT WAS MADE TO THE STATE OF PA. THE DRIVER BEGAN THE CLEAN-UP EFFORT WITH ADDITIONAL SUPPLIES PROVIDED BY THE GENERATOR. A SUPERVISOR WAS ALSO DISPATCHED FROM CLEAN HARBOR'S PITTSBURGH OFFICE. 3 - 55 GALLON DRUMS OF SPEEDI DRY WAS GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT AND IS ON THE GENERATOR'S SITE PENDING DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. IN ORDER TO PREVENT SIMILAR RELEASES IN THE FUTURE. DRIVERS HAVE BEEN RE- INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL DOME GASKETS AND SEALS ARE IN PROPER WORKING ORDER AND THAT THE DOME IS SECURED. ANY DEFECTIVE EQUIPMENT IS TO BE SERVICED OR REPLACED PRIOR TO THE TRANSPORTATION OF ANY MATERIAL.

VEHICLE OVERTURNED - FRANCE OF TRUCK PUNCTURED BOTTOM OF CARGO TANK ALLOWING APPROX. 18 BARRELLS OF LOW GRAVITY CRUDE OIL TO ESCAPE. A CONTAINMENT DYKE WAS ERECTED/OIL WAS VACUUMED AND TRANSPORTED TO BERRY PETROLEUM FACILITY/ CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED TO PROPER LAND FILL. AUTHORITIES RESPONDING STEPHENS POLICE DEPT, ARKANSAS STATE POLICE, OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES, POLLUTION CONTROL & ECOLOGY DEPT.-EL DORADO, AR., AND ARKANSAS STATE D.O.T.

OUR SALES REP WAS LOADING THE DRUM OF WASTE PGRC. ONTO LIFT GATE OF OUR TRUCK WHEN HE LOST HIS FOOTING AND SLIPPED LOSING CONTROL OF THE DRUM. THE DRUM FELL OVER AND HIT THE GROUND WHICH DISENGAGED THE LOCKING RING THAT SECURE THE TOP OF THE DRUM. THE TOP CAME OFF ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO SPILL ONTO THE PARKING LOT. OUR REP RIGHTED THE DRUM AND ATTEMPTED TO STOP THE FLOW OF WASTE ABSORBENT WIPES & ABSORBENT BOOMS. THIS ACTION PREVENTED THE FLOW FROM REACHING A NEARBY STORM DR ZONE.MOST OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED INTO A DRUM AND LABELED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE CONTAMINATED ASPHALT WAS REMOVED BY REIDEL-PTERSON ENVIROMENTAL. SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AND WE ARE WAITING RESULTS OF TEST TO DETERMINE FURTHER REMEDIATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER OF OUR COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE ON 09/30/92 DID HAVE AN ACCIDENT WHEN HECAME UP TO FAST IN AN INTERSECTION AND LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE WHILE TRYINGTO AVOID A COLLISION WITH ANOTHER PICKUP TRUCK THAT WAS STOPPING FOR THE YELLOWTRAFFIC CONTROL LIGHT AT THE INTERSECTION. WHEN OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF HISMOTOR VEHICLE WHILE TRYIN TO PASS THE PICKUP ON THE LEFT HE DID HIT THE REAREND OF THE OTHER PICKUP, AND OUR VEHICLE OVER TURNED ONTO THE DRIVERS SIDE. OUROVER TURNED TRUCK DID LOSE PRODUCT OUT OF THE TOP OF THE STAINLESS STEEL BIN(EMULSION-BLASTING AGENT NOS), THE REASON FOR LOOSING THIS PRODUCT WAS BECAUSETHE HATCH LID TO THIS BIN HAS A TENSION CATCH FOR THE HATCH, AND THE SPRINGTHAT PROVIDES THIS TENSION HAS CORROSION AND WAS NOT WORKING TO HOLD THE LID.THE DRY BULK TANK ALSO LOST PRODUCT (AMMONIUM NITRATE - OXIDIZER) WHEN THEVEHICLE WAS OVER TURNED. WHEN THE TRUCK HIT ON ITS SIDE AND SLID ON THE ROAD,THE LID TO THE ROAD FUEL TANK WAS MASHED OFF, AND THE DIESEL FUEL DID RUN OUTONTO THE ROAD ALSO. THE FREIGHT CONTAINER DID HAVE CLASS "A" EXPLOSIVES IN IT(BOOSTERS), THIS CONTAINER WAS NOT OPENED OR DAMAGED BY THE OVERTURN. THEDRIVER DID TAKE THE EXPLOSIVES "A" OUT OF THE FREIGHT CONTAINER, AWAY FROM THESPILLED MATERIALS. THE POLICE DID ARRIVE ON THE SCENE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIESHELPED CONTAIN THE MATERIALS UNTIL OUR SPILL TEAM ARRIVED TO CLEAN UP THESPILLED PRODUCT. WE ARE USING THIS FOR SELLABLE PRODUCT. ALL OF THE CLEAN UP ISUSABLE, SELLABLE PRODUCT, WE WILL USE ALL OF THIS MATERIAL. THE AREA OF THESPILL WAS COMPLETELY CLEANED UP. WE ARE TAKING MEASURES TO ENSURE THAT THESEHATCHES TO THE BINS WILL BE SECURED TIGHT, BY INSPECTING PERIODICALLY. THIS ISBEING ADDRESSED BY THE MANAGERS, AND DRIVERS OF THESE VEHICLES BY CONTINUOUSINSPECTIONS. column168: DRIVER OF OUR COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLE ON 09/30/92 DID HAVE AN ACCIDENT WHEN HECAME UP TO FAST IN AN INTERSECTION AND LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE WHILE TRYINGTO AVOID A COLLISION WITH ANOTHER PICKUP TRUCK THAT WAS STOPPING FOR THE YELLOWTRAFFIC CONTROL LIGHT AT THE INTERSECTION. WHEN OUR DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF HISMOTOR VEHICLE WHILE TRYIN TO PASS THE PICKUP ON THE LEFT HE DID HIT THE REAREND OF THE OTHER PICKUP, AND OUR VEHICLE OVER TURNED ONTO THE DRIVERS SIDE. OUROVER TURNED TRUCK DID LOSE PRODUCT OUT OF THE TOP OF THE STAINLESS STEEL BIN(EMULSION-BLASTING AGENT NOS), THE REASON FOR LOOSING THIS PRODUCT WAS BECAUSETHE HATCH LID TO THIS BIN HAS A TENSION CATCH FOR THE HATCH, AND THE SPRINGTHAT PROVIDES THIS TENSION HAS CORROSION AND WAS NOT WORKING TO HOLD THE LID.THE DRY BULK TANK ALSO LOST PRODUCT (AMMONIUM NITRATE - OXIDIZER) WHEN THEVEHICLE WAS OVER TURNED. WHEN THE TRUCK HIT ON ITS SIDE AND SLID ON THE ROAD,THE LID TO THE ROAD FUEL TANK WAS MASHED OFF, AND THE DIESEL FUEL DID RUN OUTONTO THE ROAD ALSO. THE FREIGHT CONTAINER DID HAVE CLASS "A" EXPLOSIVES IN IT(BOOSTERS), THIS CONTAINER WAS NOT OPENED OR DAMAGED BY THE OVERTURN. THEDRIVER DID TAKE THE EXPLOSIVES "A" OUT OF THE FREIGHT CONTAINER, AWAY FROM THESPILLED MATERIALS. THE POLICE DID ARRIVE ON THE SCENE AND LOCAL AUTHORITIESHELPED CONTAIN THE MATERIALS UNTIL OUR SPILL TEAM ARRIVED TO CLEAN UP THESPILLED PRODUCT. WE ARE USING THIS FOR SELLABLE PRODUCT. ALL OF THE CLEAN UP ISUSABLE, SELLABLE PRODUCT, WE WILL USE ALL OF THIS MATERIAL. THE AREA OF THESPILL WAS COMPLETELY CLEANED UP. WE ARE TAKING MEASURES TO ENSURE THAT THESEHATCHES TO THE BINS WILL BE SECURED TIGHT, BY INSPECTING PERIODICALLY. THIS ISBEING ADDRESSED BY THE MANAGERS, AND DRIVERS OF THESE VEHICLES BY CONTINUOUSINSPECTIONS. WE HAVE PLACED THE DRIVER OF THIS VEHICLE ON PROBATION, AND HE HASBEEN SUSPENDED FROM DRIVING UNTIL THE IINVESTIGATION FOR THIS ACCIDENT INCOMPLETED.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROX 2:15AM ON THURSDAY, SEPT 17TH 1992, A 20 FT ISO TANK CONTAINER SITTING ON A CHASSIS IN THE MIDDLE OF THE YANG MING TERMINAL CONTAINER YARD WAS FOUND LAYING ON ITS SIDE. A SMALL AMOUNT (APPROX 2 CUPS) OF THE 31% HYDROGEN PEROXIDE LIQUID CARGO HAD LEAKED OUT OF A GAUGE ON THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE CHASSIS TO WHICH THE TANK CONTAINER WAS ATTACHED HAD APPARENTLY BEEN HIT BY ANOTHER VEHICLE (A CHASSIS BEING PULLED BY A UTILITY TRACTOR) AND KNOCKED OVER.  A POLLUTION RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, ANCON ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, WAS CALLED OUT TO CLEANUP THE SPILL AND OFFLOAD THE DAMAGED TANK CONTAINER.  ANCON PROVIDED A 4,000 GALLON PLASTIC "BAKER" TANK FOR OFFLOADING THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE.  HALF OF THE CARGO IN THE DAMAGED TANK CONTAINER WAS OFFLOADED TO STOP THE LEAK AND FACILITATE RIGHTING THE TANK CONTAINER.  AFTER THE CONTAINER WAS RIGHTED, REMOVED FROM THE DAMAGED CHASSIS AND PLACED ON ANOTHER CHASSIS, THE REMAINING CARGO WAS TRANSFERRRED.  THE PLAN WAS TO TRANSFER THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE INTO ANOTHER ISO TANK CONTAINER ON FRIDAY (18TH) OR SAT (19TH) AS ONE WAS SUPPOSEDLY AVAILABLE LOCALLY.  HOWEVER, YANK MING TERMINAL HAD BEEN GIVEN ERRONEOUS INFORMATION AND IT TOOK NEARLY 4 DAYS OF INTENSIVE SEARCH TO LOCATE AN APPROPRIATE CONTAINER.  AT APPROX 2AM ON TUESDAY SEPT 22ND, FUMES/WHITE COLORED VAPORS WERE FOUND TO BE EMANATING FROM THE TOP OF THE BAKER TANK. ALL OF THE REQUISITE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED, THE TANK ISOLATED AND A MAJOR RESPONSE EFFORT CONTRACTOR.  CHEMTREC, AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE, WERE ALL CONTACTED FOR TECHNICAL INFORMATION. ALL RECOMMENDED THAT THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE NOT BE TRANSFERRED OUT OF THE BAKER TANK UNTIL IT HAD COMPLETED THE OXIDATION (DECOMPOSITION) REACTIONS; NO ONE KNEW WHY THE REACTION STARTED IN THE BAKER TANK.  VARIOUS HYPOTHESES WERE OFFERED INCLUDING; PRESENCE OF AN ORGANIC CONTAMINANT IN THE BAKER TANK (HOWEVER, THE TANK HAD BEEN CERTIFIED AS CLEAN BY BAKER WHEN IT WAS RENTED BY ANCON AND DELIVERED TO THE TERMINAL); CONTAMINATION BY THE TRANSFER HOSES AND/OR PUMP USED TO OFFLOAD THE DAMAGED TANK CONTAINER (HOWEVER, THE PUMP AND HOSES WERE CLEANED PRIOR TO BEING BROUGHT TO THE TERMINAL AND NO EVIDENCE OF CONTAMINATION WAS OBSERVED IN THEM PRIOR TO TRANSFER); AND REACTION WITH/OR CONTAMINATION FROM THE AIR IN THE TANK OR WHICH ENTERED THE TANK AS IT SAT ON THE TERMINAL (2 DAYS OF THE 4 DAYS IT SAT ON THE TERMINAL INCLUDED VERY FOGGY NIGHTS AND SIGNIGICANT TEMPERATURE CHANGES).  THE LATER WAS THE CONSENSUS OF THE AGENCIES AND THE TECHNICAL EXPERTS AS THE MOST PROBABLE CAUSE; CHEMICAL ANALYSES (OF THE SAMPLES TAKEN FOLLOWING THE REACTIVE PHASE) DO NOT INDICATE PRESENCE OF ANY CONTAMINANTS (SEE ENCLOSERE 3); THEREFORE, THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE "EXOTHERMIC, OXIDATION/DECOMPOSITION REACTION" OF THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE INSIDE THE BAKER TANK REMAINS UNCONFIRMED.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PROVIDED EQUIPMENT TO COOL THE EXTERIOR OF THE BAKER TANK USING 2 FIRE MONITORS HOOKED TO A HYDRANT AND BACK-U

1 CARTON OF ACID TO NORWHICH UNIVERSITY WAS PLACED ON TOP OF ELECTRIC MOTOR WHICH ITSELF WAS FIBERBOARD PACKAGED FELL THROUGH ONTO MOTOR AND BROKE TWO GLASSES OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID.  SMALL SPILLAGE ONTO ELECTRIC MOTOR.  PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES WILL BE PRACTICED IN THE FUTURE.
DRUM SMASHED BY LOADER. PRODUCT JUST RECLASSIFED FROM ORM-A UN1897 ST. ANDREWS CROSS TO POISONOUS 6.1 UN2810.

WHILE STOPPING FOR FUEL AT THE SOONERS CORNER TRUCK STOP IN PERRY, OKLAHOMA, THE DRIVER CONDUCTED A VEHICLE INSPECTION AND NOTICED AN ACUMULATION OF ICE UNDER THE VALVE SEAT OF PCV-1 (PRESSURE CONTROL VALVE). IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS ICE BUILD-UP ALLOWED THE 17 PSIG SAFETY VALVE TO REMAIN ACTIVE IN ADDITION TO THE 50 PSIG SAFETY VALVE.  THIS CAUSED THE PRESSURE TO BEGIN RELIEVING AT 17 PSIG INSTEAD OF 50 PSIG.  (NOTE: BECAUSE THE TRAILER ONLY HAD RESIDUAL VAPOR, THE 17 PSIG SAFETY SHOULD HAVE BEEN INACTIVE.)  THE DRIVER VENTED THE TRAILER DOWN TO 2 PSIG WHICH RELEASED 7,680 STD. CUBIC FEET OF HYDROGEN GAS TO THE ATMOSPHERE.  BEFORE PROCEEDING, THE DRIVER ASSURED THAT THE VALVE (PCV-1) HAD COMPLETELY THAWED AND RETURNED TO AMBIENT TEMPERATURE.  THE VALVE AND ASSOCIATED PIPING WAS INSPECTED AFTER RETURNING TO NEW ORLEANS.  NO DEFECTS WERE NOTED.  OCCASSIONAL ICE ACCUMULATION IS NORMAL.

DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED "NEVER TO TRY TO ADJUST ANY PART OF THE UNLOADING PROCESS WHILE PRODUCT IS FLOWING" THEY ARE TO CHECK FITTINGS PRIOR TO STARTING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING DRUM QUANTITIES OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS EN ROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVE. IN BRAINTREE, MA TO ALLWORTH INC. LOCATED AT 101 SOUTH PARK DRIVE IN MT. PLEASANT, TN. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT A REST AREA LOCATED AT MILE MARKER 25 ON ROUTE 81 IN MARLOWE, WV. PRIOR TO DEPARTING THE REST ARE, THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE (APPR. ONE PINT) OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT OF THE REST AREA. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY COVERED THE PRODUCT WITH  SPEEDI DRY AND PROCEEDED TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. UPON EXAMINATION OF THE CARGO, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM CHIME OF A DRUM CONTAINING ACETONE AND TOLUENE HAD BEGUN TO LEAK. THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN THE OVERPACK. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

A VAN TRUCK CONTAINING DRUM QUANTITIES OF HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS EN ROUTE FROM CHICAGO BRIDGE & IRON TECHNICAL SERVICES COMPANY LOCATED AT 1501 N. DIVSION STREET LOCATED IN PLAINFIELD, IL TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 S. STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO,IL. AS THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE ENTERED THE CLEAN HARBOR'S FACILITY, HE NOTICED MATERIAL HAD BEGUN TO LEAK FROM THE WASTE HAULING PORTION OF THE VEHICLE. HE IMMEDIATELY PLACED A 5 GALLON PAIL UNDER THE LEAK AND SPREAD SPEEDI DRY OVER THE SPILLED MATERIAL. HE THEN CONTACTED THE FACILITY COMPLIANCE MANAGER OF CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO,INC. WHO, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE ILLINOIS ENVIROMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (INCIDENT # 922682) AND ORGANIZED A RESPONSE CREW TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL. THE DRIVER, ALONG WITH FACILITY PERSONNEL IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND PROCEEDED TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING DRUM. THE CREW THEN COLLECTED THE CONTAMINATED SPEEDI DRY USED TO CLEAN-UP THE SPILL. ALL MATERIAL GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINERIZED IN 1 X 55 GALLON DRUM AND WILL BE SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

OUR TRACTOR AND TRAILER WAS TRAVELING FROM PHOENIX, AZ. TO EL PASO TEXAS, WHEN OUR TRAILER ARRIVED AT OUR EL PASO TERMINAL, THE TERMINAL MANAGER OPENED THE OVERHEAD DOOR TO DISCOVER THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD A SMALL PUNCTURE AND SPILLED ABOUT 6 OZS OF COPPER CYANIDE ON THE TRAILER FLOOR. FIVE OF THE NINE DERAILED CARS (DUPX 38363, DUPX 38258, DUPX 38196 AND DUPX 38297) WERE COVERED HOPPER CARS CONTAINING A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, SOLID, N.O.S. (ADIPIC ACID). column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: SORT SUPERVISOR SAVE HARP REPORTED TO HAZ MAT DISPATCH, A SPILL AT DOOR A-16.  THE SPILL WAS REPORTED AT A-16 FEED CATWALK.  THE BOX WAS STEAMING; POSSIBLE DRY ICE.  I, FRAN VANCE, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR AND ADDIE CAMPTON, PART TIME HAZ MAT SPILL TECH, ARRIVED ON SCENE.  WE FOUND A FIBREBOARD BOX APPROXIMATELY 36" x 36" x 24" STANDING ON END EMITTING A STEAM-LIKE SUBSTANCE FROM THE BOTTOM.  AT THIS TIME FROM THE APPEARANCE OF THE STEAM, THE BOX APPEARED TO CONTAIN A POSSIBLE CRYOGENIC MATERIAL.  THE BOX WAS PLACED DOWN FLAT TO POSSIBLY STOP THE FLOW OF THE MATERIAL.  THIS CAUSED THE BOX TO EMIT MORE OF THE STEAM WHICH NOW COULD BE SEEN AS A FINE YELLOW POWDER.  THE BOX WAS PLACED ON ITS END AGAIN AND PUT INTO A LARGE WHITE PLASTIC BAG.  BOTH ADDIE CAMPTON AND MYSELF WERE EXPOSED TO THE POWDER. THE CONTAINER WAS TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. CLEARED THE SCENE AND ENROUTE TO HAZ MAT SORT. THE PART TIME SPILL SPECIALIST AND I WASHED THE POWDER FROM OUR AFFECTED AREAS (ARMS AND NECK).  FOR DECONTAMINATION, I, FRANCE VANCE REMOVED MY COVERALLS AND PLACED THEM INTO A PLASTIC BAG.  AFTER REDRESSING, WE CONTINUED OUR INVESTIGATION OF THE BOX. AREA BARRICADED OFF FOR BOX AND CONTENT INSPECTION.  TYVEK SUITS AND CARTRIDGE MASKS WERE DONNED.  THE PLASTIC BAG CONTAINING THE BOX WAS OPENED TO BE TWO (2) ABC FIRE EXTINGUISHERS @ 10 LBS EACH.  ONE OF THE FIRE EXTIGUISHERS WAS MISSING ITS' LOCKING PIN.  THERE WAS NO INNER PACKAGING MATERIAL OR CUSHIONING TO KEEP THE EXTINGUISHERS STABLE IN THE BOX.  THE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS WERE IN A BOX THAT WAS TOO LARGE; ENABLING THEM TO MOVE AROUND AND ROLL INTO EACH OTHER CAUSING THE ONE MISSING THE LOCKING PIN TO DISCHARGE.  THE FIRE EXTINGUISHERS WERE PLACED IN SEPARATE PLASTIC BAGS.  THE FIBREBOARD BOX WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND ALL OF THIS WAS TAGGED AND HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATON.  EQUIPMENT WAS PUT BACK INTO SERVICE AND THE SCENE WAS CLEAR. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE SHIPMENT IS UNDER LOCK AND KEY AT OUR HAZ SORT FACILITY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET HAD BEEN REQUESTED FROM THE SHIPPER.

column168: AT 0205 SORT SUPERVISOR, DON COOK, REPORTED AN ODOR IN A UNIT LOAD DEVICE. UPON ARRIVAL ON SCENE I, TONY FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATRIALS COORDINATOR, AND PART-TIME SPILL SPECIALIST NEAL VAN SAUN, FOUND THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE THAT WAS EMMITTING THE ODOR OF FINGERNAIL POLISH.  I DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASK AND STARTED UNLOADING THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE.  INSIDE I FOUND ONE FIBERBOARD BOX WITH A RED LIQUID ON THE CORNER.  I OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX AND INSIDE WAS 50 GLASS RECEPTICLES, EACH CONTAINING .05 FLUID OUNCES EACH.  THERE WAS NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ-MAT SORT, IN THE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS CABINET, PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

ON 9/17, WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER 28 8620 FROM HARRISBURG, DOCKMAN JOHN CAMPBELL NOTICED 1 DRUM OF THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING FROM THE VENT (BUNG) HOLE ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  THIS 1 DRUM WAS HELD AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER ON PRO/184244 152 XO PER ROBERT WITTPENN W/SHIPPER.

JOHN GORDON OPENED TRAILER 11-4430 X-DLS (405BAY) AND DISCOVERED 1 DRUM LEAKING.  AT THIS TIME 1 EVACUATED THE AREA AND CALLED CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER.  SHIPPER ADVISED TO CALL CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL FOR CLEAN-UP. CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL ADVISED ME DRUMS WERE DEFECTIVE.  ALSO IMPROER PACKAGING FOR THIS PRODUCT.  HAD SHIPPER USED PROPER PACKAGING, I BELIEVE THIS INCIDENT COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) C.C. SHUPE WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR DOWX 6971 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP.  SSA/HM SHUPE CONTACTED SPECIAL AGENT (SA) PARKS AND REQUESTED HIS ASSISTANCE. INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLING FROM THE RUBBER COATED FLANGES AND SPACER ON THE LIQUID LINE.  THE METAL SHIMS WERE MISSING FROM UNDER FOUR OF THE EIGHT BOLTS WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE FLANGES AND SPACER.  LIMESTONE WAS DELIVERED AND SPREAD TO NEUTRALIZE PRODUCT.  METAL WASHERS WERE INSTALLED ON EACH OF THE FOUR BOLT HEADS AND THE NUTS TO SECURE THE LOAD FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. ALL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO APPROPRIATE AGENCIES.

SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS 9SA/HM) C.D. HUGGINS WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING INTERMODAL CONTAINER, SECS 543058, AT THE UPMF RAMP IN SALT LAKE CITY.  THE SALT LAKE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. SA/HM HUGGINS RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CONTAINER HAD BEEN DROPPED WHEN BEING LIFTED FROM FLAT CAR TTWX 971696 DUE TO A DEFECTIVE LINKAGE IN THE TWIST LOCK ON THE RIGHT FRONT SIDE WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTAINER TO DISENGAGE FROM THE PACKER.  FURTHER INSPECTION DETERINED THAT THE LEAK OCCURRED FROM THE BOTTOM END OUTLET VALVE.  LEAK HAD SLOWED TO A SAMLL TRICKLE AND PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED IN A PAIL. PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO UPUU 630037 BY UNITED WARD TRANSFER. BRENDA MARSH OF DOW HEMICAL AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: WHILE CONDUCTUNG ROUTINE INSPECTIONS, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) F.H. LERCH NOTED TANK CAR KCCX 2491 HAD ABURST FRANGIBLE DIS IN THE SAFETY VENT HOUSING.  SA/HM LERCH REPLACED THE BURST BS&B, 100 PSI, FRANGIBLE DIS WITH ANEW CDC, 100 PSI DISC WHICH SECURED THE CAR.  THERE WAS NOT EVIDENCE OF LIQUID RELEASE OF THE PRODUCT. JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC, NEBRASKA ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENT, AND JAMES KLAR OF AMERICAN MICRODOT, WERE ALL NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) C.C. SHUPE WAS NOTIFIED THAT DOWX 6902 WAS LEAKING HYDROCHLORIC ACID IN DEXTER, MO.  DEXCTER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE.  CAR WAS MOVED OUT OF THE CITY LIMITED. SSA/HM SHUPE RESPONDED AND DIRECTOR OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGEMENT, L.R. TIERNEY, INFORMED SSA/HM SHUPE THAT DEXTER FIRE CHIEF REPORTED THAT LEAK APPEARED TO BE FROM A WELD ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE CAR.  SSA/HM SHUPE'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM A HOLE APPROXIMATELY 1/2 X 1/4" IN SIZE.  THIS WAS DUE TO A RUPTURE IN THE INSIDE LINER.  HOLE WAS PLUGGED AND DIKE WAS BUILT TO CONTAIN PRODUCT AND LIMESTONE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT.  RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTRACTED FOR TRANSFER AND CLEAN UP.  PRODUCTR WAS TRANSFERRED INTO DOWX 7974. REMAINING PRODUCT IN DMAAGED TANK CAR WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH LIMESTONE AND STENCILED "DO NOT LOAD LEAKING TANK".  CHEMTREC AND ALL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

ON SEPTEMBER 16, 1992, LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (FS), INC. HAD UN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF AN RQ WASTE FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S. (VINYL ACETATE) CLASS 3, UN1993, PG111. THE INVIDENT WAS DISCOVERED UPON ARRIVAL AT LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (RECOVERY), INC. IN CROWLEY, LOUISIANA. AT THAT TIME, THE DRIVER NOTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL ON THE REAR DOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER.  THE DRIVER NOTIFIED APPROPRIATE SAFETY PERSONNEL IN THE FACILITY.  AFTER TAKING NECESSARY SAFETY PRECAUTIONS, THE REAR DOOR WAS OPENED.  THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR REPORTED THAT ONE 55 GALLON DRUM HAD LEAKED FROM THE DRUM.  THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT 92-3413).  THE LOUISIANA DEQ WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT 92-1856).  THE SPILLED MATERIAL DID NOT EQUAL OR EXCEED THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY.  OUR INTERNAL INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT IMPROPER BRACING WAS THE CAUSE OF THE OVERTURNED DRUM.  THE DRIVERS INVOLVED IN TRANSPORTING THIS LOAD HAD BEEN COUNSELED WITH RESPECT TO PROPER LOADING AND BRACING OF DRUMS.

ADVISED BY E. DIETZ, CARFOREMAN THAT MECHANICAL SHOP PERSONNEL WERE INSPECTING CAR ACFX 12990 (PRIOR TO WELDING ON CAR) WITH "GASTREC 8800" AND OBTAINED DETECTABLE READING.  CAR WAS ISOLATED IN THE SHOP TRACK, AND CHEMTREC CALLED FOR SHIPPER ASSISTANCE.  CONTACT MADE WITH SHIPPER WHO ADVISED THEY WOULD RESPONSE TO INSPECT CAR.  CHEMICAL SOLVENTS PERSONNEL INSPECTED CAR AND FOUND MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE,  BOTLS TIGHTENED AND CAR SECURED AT 1530 HRS.

WHILE INSPECTING LOAD AT TRUCKSTO, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT MATERIAL WAS LEAKING THROUGH BOTTOM OF OCEAN GOING CONTAINER ONTO DECK OF FLATBED TRAILER THIS WAS AN INBOND SHIPMENT AND CUSTOMS WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION. THE TERRELL FIRE DEPT AND TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY WERE BOTH NOTIFIED.  IT WAS THEN DETERMINED A CREW WAS GOING TO BE NEEDED TO REPAIR LEAKING CONTAINERS.  PERMISSION WAS GRANTED BY CUSTOMS OFFICIALS TO BREAK SEAL.  EMTECH, A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR FROM FT WORTH, TX WAS CONTRACTED.  THREE DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  THESE DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED.  NO WASTE MATERIAL WAS GENERATED.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT NO 135192).

ON SEPT 14, 1992 AT APPROX. 2215 HRS W HILE UNLOADING HP 266 SUPERVISOR SEALAS NOTICED THE CONTAINER WHICH CONTAINED THE NON FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  HE IMMEDIATELY REPORTED IT TO CARGO SUPERVISOR VILLA.  VILLA REMOVED THE CONTAINER TO THE CARGO AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  SLIGHT VENTING OCCURED DURING UNLOADING AND SUPERVISOR VILLA WENT TO HUMANA HOSPITAL TO BE CHECKED.  THE INTEGRITY OF THE CONTENTS OF THE CONTAINER FAA CASFO NOTIFIED AT 0945 15SEPT92.  SHIPMENT RELEASED TO FEDERAL EXPRESS TO FINAL DESTINATION AFTER FAA RELEASE.

MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE, WAS NOTIFIED BY YARDMASTER, FLOYD WHITE, THAT CREWS HAD REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR CAR GATX 94401.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT MANAGER STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, CHIEF INSPECTOR A. D. MATY, AAR, AGREED TO RESPOND. INSPECTOR MATY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM THE BASE OF THE "A" END LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE.  THE FOUR SECUREMENTS NUTS WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT ON THE PRESSURE PLATE STUDS.  THE NUTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  ALL FITTINGS WERE CHECKED FOR SECUREMENT AND IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE NUTS ON THE "B" END LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WERE LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT BUT THERE WAS NOT EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE. JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC AND MR. ROSE OF FARMLAND WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 900 HOURS, SEPTEMBER 16, 1992 EMPLOYEES AT CONRAIL'S HILLARY YARD IN DANVILLE, IL OBSERVED LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR ACFX 84057. AN INSPECTION REVEALED A RUPTURED DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY. MR. DICK ASTELL FROM FLEXEL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISC. CAR FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1130 SEPTEMBER 29, 1992, FRA HAZ/MAT INSPECTOR J. CONNELLY DISCOVERED LIQUID SEEPAGE NEAR THE TOP VALVE AREA OF TANK CAR 14703 (CRUDE OIL, PETROLEUM) WHILE CONDUCTING AN INBOUND INSPECTION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TANK CARS AT CONRAIL'S BUCKEYE YARD IN COLUMBUS, OH. PENNSOIL RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT 1700 HOURS AND REPAIRED AND REPLACED 0NE MANWAY GASKET AND ONE SAFETY VALVE GASKET. CAR RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTAION AT 1845 HOURS.

WHILE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND ON PA STATE RT 33, APPROXIMATELY 12, 50 POUND BAGS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE FELL FROM THE TRAILER ONTO THE ROADWAY AND RIPPED OPEN.  THE DRIVER STOPPED THE TRUCK AND TRIED TO PICKUP THE TORN BAGS COMING INTO CONTACT WITH THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE POLICE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE EASTON HOSPITAL AND TREATED AND RELEASED SUFFERING FROM BURNS TO HIS ARMS.  THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (REPORT NO.138776).  THE S.B. LANE OF RT 33 WAS SHUT DOWN WHILE CLEAN UP WAS BEING PERFORMED.  THE HECKTOWN FIRE COMPANY ASSISTED KEYSTONE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES IN THE CLEAN-UP.  TWO (2) 85 GAL. OVERPACK DRUMS OF WASTE MATERIAL WAS PICKED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY KEYSTONE ENVIRONMENTAL.  THE UNDAMAGED BAGS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE WERE TAKEN OFF THE TRISM TRAILER AND PLACED IN STORAGE FOR PICK UP BY THE SHIPPER.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: I WAS CALLED AT APPROXIMATELY 3 A.M. ON 9/12/92 (SAT) AND ADVISED BY THE SHIFT FOREMAN AT THE CENEX REFINERY THAT THEY HAD BEEN CALLED BY CHEMTREC. THE SHIFT FOREMAN ADVISED ME THAT ONE OF OUR TRAILERS WAS LEAKING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AND THAT THE SHERIFFS DEPT.  AND FIRE DEPT WERE AT THE SCENE.  I CALLED BOB REED, A DEPTY FOR HILL COUNTY AND HE ASKED WHERE THEY COULD LOCATE THE DRIVER.  I TOLD HIM THE DRIVER WAS AT THE ELTORO MOTEL ACROSS THE STREET.  HE TOLD ME THAT THE PARKED TRAILER WAS LEAKING AA AT A RATE OF APPROX. 50 DROPS PER MIN.  THE DRIVER, TERRY WANNER CAME TO THE SCENE AND ADVISED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES THAT THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER WERE LEAKING.  THEY LET HIM TAKE THE TRAILER AND HE PROCEEDED TO EDGAR, MT, DELIVERED THE PRODUCT AND RETURNED THE TRAILER TO OUR SHOP IN LAUREL, MT (1011 HIGHWAY 212 S.)  THE TRAILER WAS THEN PUT OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL THE NECESSARY REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.  REPAIRS ARE CURRENTLY BEING MADE TO THE TRAILER (UNIT #7653661).  THIS INCIDENT WAS ALSO REPORTED AT THE TIME OF OCCURANCE TO THE MONTANA SPILL HOTLINE # AND THEY REPORTED TO KEN GRIEB OF THE MONTANA DISASTER AND EMERGENCY SERVICES.  THIS INCIDENT HAS ALSO BEEN REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL EPA, REG. #8 (KAREN MORRE) IN DENVER, CO ON 9/15/92.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T. M. ROBINSON WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN ADDIS, LA.  SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET NOZZLE CAP OF TANK CAR GATX 13381.  SSA/HM ROBINSON TIGHTENED THE OPERATING STEM OF THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ONE TURN WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK OF PRODUCT.  CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, WEST BATON ROUGE PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE, CHEMTREC, AND DOW CHEMICAL.

column168: HAZMAT RECEIVED REPORT OF TWO TANK CARS VENTING VAPORS FROM THE TOP AT TILFORD YARD, ATLANTA, GA.  THE CARS WERE SET OUT AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER, WP HARRISON, RESPONDED AND REPLACED BLOWN RUPTURE DISKS IN BOTH CARS.

COMMENTS HRS129 9-25-92 RECEIVED TRLR 29 2116 FROM MOO WITH A LEAKING DRUM OF POISON ORM E. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND BILL GASSON W/CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED. CHEMTREC REPORTED THE LEAKAGE TO TERRY CHUBALL WITH MILES LABS.  TERRY CONTACTED ME AT HRS AND ADVISED OF CLEAN UP PROCEDURES.  HE ALSO FAXED A COPY OF THE MSDO AS A BACK UP.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED. THE DAMAGED DRUM IN PENDING THE OFFICAL RETURN LABELS FROM MILES LABS.  WE ALSO RECEIVED RETURN AUTHORIZATION NUMBER RC 2131 FROM MILES FOR THE RETURN MOVE.  THE CHEMICAL ABSORBANT AND THE DAMAGED DRUM ARE BING RETURNED TO MILES IN NEWARK, NJ ON AN XO DEADHEAD BILL #167290992.  HAZARDOUS INCIDENT REPORT IS BEING COMPLETED AND FORWARDED TO THE SAFETY DEPT. FOR HANDLING.  THE OFFICE MGR IN MOO WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SITUATION. -AJ-HRS/129

COLES DRIVER PICKED UP 3 DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THE DRUMS WERE SECURED APPR. 1/2 WAY UP WITH A LOAD BAR. AS THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING THROUGH BRIDGE CONSTRUCTION OF RTE. 24 S, AVON, MA -- THE CARGO SHIFTED. ANOTHER MOTOR VEHICLE ALERTED DRIVER OF THE LEAKAGE FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. COLES DRIVER STOPPED IMMEDIATELY, NOTIFIED ACOLES DISPATCH IN LOWELL. THE AVON FIRE & POLICE DEPT. WERE NOTIFIED ALONG WITH JETLINE SERVICES, INC. OF STOUGHTON, MASS, THE MASS DEP WAS ALSO CONTACTED, LEONARD PINAUD RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. COLES DRIVER AND THE OTHER DRIVER WHO OFFERED ASSISTENCE AT THE SCENE WERE BOTH OBSERVED AT THE SCENE BY THE AVON AMBULANCE TECHNICIANS FOR POSSIBLE INHALATION PROBLEMS, (BOTH DRIVERS WERE UN-AFFECTED). AFTER THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED, THE UNIT WAS TAKEN TO THE AVON DPW YARD. JETLINE TRANSPORTED AND DISPOSED OF THE WASTE MATERIALS (PUT IN OVERPAC - POLY BONDICO - DRUMS WITH LINERS). THE TRAILER WAS THEN TAKEN BACK TO THE COLES TERMINAL WHERE IT WAS THOROUGHLY RINSED AS PER THE INSTRUCTIONS OF THE DEP.  MASS STATE MANIFEST # G116307

column168: MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY YARDMASTER THAT CAR HAD BEEN SET OUT DUE TO COFC USPC 37226 HAD THE REAR GATE OPEN AN DIRT HAD SPILLED ONTO THE DECK OF THE FLAT CAR.  CONTAINER HAD BOTH SAFETY CHAINS ON THE REAR DOOR TORN OFF AND THE STEEL EYE ON THE SAFETY RATCHET WAS TORN LOOSE ALLOWING THE TAILGATE DOOR TO SWING OPEN AND DIRT TO SPILL OUT ONTO THE DECK OF THE CAR.  APPARENTLY SOME TYPE OF IMPACT HAD OCCURRED. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR MR. KURT B. ECKLE OF USPCI TO INSPECT LOAD AND HAVE THE REMEDIAL PERSONNEL OF USPCI RELOAD THE SOIL AND SECURE THE REAR DOOR.
